{"key":"post-12696918","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12696918</id>\n<content>Heat causes the mushrooms to grow hollow stems, but that's hardly a problem.&amp;nbsp; Mushrooms are mushrooms.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;However, I see no perlite in your terrarium.&amp;nbsp; I'd ditch the humidifier first of all.&amp;nbsp; From the looks of your substrate and mushrooms, I'd say you've waterlogged it.&amp;nbsp; A waterlogged substrate will perform poorly at best, resulting in small mushrooms.&amp;nbsp; If you want an automated setup, put a shotgun terrarium in the middle of a room and you're done.&amp;nbsp; Don't forget to expose to a very bright window, or use a 6500K fluorescent lamp 12 hours per day.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;P cubensis&lt;/i&gt; will fruit well at temperatures which would fry the mycelium during colonization.&amp;nbsp; That's why they fruit well in Texas and Florida when the temperatures are near 100F.&amp;nbsp; I'd worry less about heat since it's indoors and worry more about proper humidity without flooding the substrates, which perlite is perfectly suited for.&amp;nbsp; I'd drill holes for fresh air exchange and get rid of the fans.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Everyone seems to want to automate terrariums.&amp;nbsp; The simplest methods of all are the best.&amp;nbsp; Use perlite for humidity and holes for fresh air, plus sunlight from a bright window for light.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I also don't run AC during the summer.&amp;nbsp; We open windows up at night to cool the house off, and then close them during the heat of the day to allow our insulation to keep it cool.&amp;nbsp; As soon as the sun goes down, we open the windows back up.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12697032</next>\n<prev>12696805</prev>\n<first>12696659</first>\n<last>12715541</last>\n<when>1275849024</when>\n<utime>06/06/10 09:30 PM</utime>\n</post>"}